# Remotes Structure with Headers

The `headers` field in the remotes array is **an array of objects**, not a map/object.

## Example 1: AdAdvisor MCP Server (v1.0.1)
```json
{
  "type": "streamable-http",
  "url": "https://api.adadvisor.ai/mcp",
  "headers": [
    {
      "description": "Bearer token (adv_sk_...). Get key: https://...",
      "isRequired": true,
      "isSecret": true,
      "name": "Authorization"
    }
  ]
}
```

## Example 2: AgentDM
```json
{
  "type": "streamable-http",
  "url": "https://api.agentdm.ai/api/v1/grid",
  "headers": [
    {
      "description": "Bearer token for authentication (e.g., 'Bearer agentdm_...')...",
      "isRequired": true,
      "isSecret": true,
      "name": "Authorization"
    }
  ]
}
```

## Example 3: Contabo (VPS) MCP Server
```json
{
  "type": "streamable-http",
  "url": "https://contabo.run.mcp.com.ai/mcp",
  "headers": [
    {
      "description": "Bearer token for authenticating with the Contabo API...",
      "isRequired": true,
      "format": "string",
      "isSecret": true,
      "name": "Authorization"
    },
    {
      "description": "Optional request ID for tracing (recommended...)",
      "format": "string",
      "name": "x-request-id"
    }
  ]
}
```

**Key observation:** Headers is consistently structured as an array where each element represents a single HTTP header requirement with metadata properties.

